Here's how to handle all three scenarios in .NET MAUI:

### 1. Detect the current system theme

```csharp
AppTheme currentTheme = Application.Current.RequestedTheme;
// Returns AppTheme.Light, AppTheme.Dark, or AppTheme.Unspecified
```

### 2. Subscribe to theme change events

```csharp
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    AppTheme newTheme = e.RequestedTheme;
    Debug.WriteLine($"Theme changed to: {newTheme}");

    // Update UI or trigger logic here
};
```

This fires in real time whenever the user toggles dark/light mode in device settings.

### 3. Force a specific theme (override system setting)

```csharp
// Lock to dark mode regardless of system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Lock to light mode
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Light;

// Revert to following the system setting
Application.Current.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;
```

### Full example in `App.xaml.cs`

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new AppShell();

        Debug.WriteLine($"Current theme: {RequestedTheme}");

        RequestedThemeChanged += OnThemeChanged;
    }

    private void OnThemeChanged(object sender, AppThemeChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        Debug.WriteLine($"System theme changed to: {e.RequestedTheme}");
        // Respond to the change — update colors, swap icons, etc.
    }

    // Call from a settings page to let the user override
    public void SetUserTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        UserAppTheme = theme; // AppTheme.Unspecified reverts to system
    }
}
```

### XAML-side adaptive resources

You can also react declaratively using `AppThemeBinding`:

```xml
<Label Text="Hello"
       TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=Black, Dark=White}" />
```

These bindings update automatically when the theme changes — no code-behind needed.

**Key points:**
- `RequestedTheme` = what the OS reports.
- `UserAppTheme` = your app's override (`Unspecified` = follow OS).
- `RequestedThemeChanged` fires on OS changes even when `UserAppTheme` is set, but the UI only follows the override.
